,"en":{"1500–10 June 1531":"1500–10 June 1531","1500–1558":"1500–1558","1516–1544":"1516–1544","1530–1603":"1530–1603","–Male":"Deceased","1500–1531":"1500–1531","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","10 June 1531":"10 June 1531","1516":"1516","23 nov 1530":"23 November 1530","1603":"1603","Ross Castle, Ballbar, Ross Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Ross  Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Balblair, Ross, Scotland":"Balblair, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacIntosh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McIntosh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McIntosh","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Toisich</b> ‘son of the chief’. Compare   Mackintosh  .","History: Clan <i>Mackintosh</i> is a Highland Scottish clan claiming descent from Shaw McDuff, a 12th-century chief (second son of Duncan, Earl of Fife), who established the traditional family seat at Perry, Morays. The chiefs of Clan Mackintosh have been regarded as leaders of the Chattan Confederation since 1291."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Grzegorz, Irena, Lucyna, Witold.","Polish (mainly <b>Łada</b>) and Czech (Moravian): from a short form of the Polish personal name <i>Ładysław</i>, Czech <i>Ladislav</i>, both from <i>Vladislav</i> (Latinized as <i>Ladislaus</i>), a Slavic name composed of the elements <i>vlad</i> ‘to rule’ (from Old Slavic <i>vlasti</i>, later <i>vladati</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). Compare 2 below.","Hungarian: from <i>Lad(a)</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Ladomér</i>, a Hungarian form of Slavic <i>Vladimir</i> (see   Lado   2, compare 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah MacIntosh Lady of Balmachy was born in 1500, in Ross, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons with Hugh de Ross IV. She died on 10 June 1531, in her hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1500–10 June 1531":"1500–10. juuni 1531","1500–1558":"1500–1558","1516–1544":"1516–1544","1530–1603":"1530–1603","–Male":"Surnud","1500–1531":"1500–1531","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","10 June 1531":"10. juuni 1531","1516":"1516","23 nov 1530":"23. november 1530","1603":"1603","Ross Castle, Ballbar, Ross Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Ross  Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Balblair, Ross, Scotland":"Balblair, Ross and Cromarty, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–10 June 1531":"1500–10. kesäkuuta 1531","1500–1558":"1500–1558","1516–1544":"1516–1544","1530–1603":"1530–1603","–Male":"Kuollut","1500–1531":"1500–1531","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","10 June 1531":"10. kesäkuuta 1531","1516":"1516","23 nov 1530":"23. marraskuuta 1530","1603":"1603","Ross Castle, Ballbar, Ross Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Ross  Comarty, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Balblair, Ross, Scotland":"Balblair, Ross and Cromarty, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1500–10 June 1531":"1500–10